  <title>Examples A</title>
 
<paragraphs>
  <title>Coulomb's Law</title>
  
  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        If <m>3.2\times10^{20}</m> electrons move through a cigarette lighter during its operation, 
        how many coulombs of charge moved through it?
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <me>
          Q = N_{e}q_{e}
        </me>
        <me>
          = (3.2\times10^{20})\times(1.6\times10^{-19}) = 51.2 \,C
        </me>
         </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          How many coulombs of positive charge are there in 1.00 kg of plutonium? 
          Given: atomic mass of plutonium atom is 244 and each plutonium atom has 94 protons.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p> From eqn. <xref ref="eqn-charge1"/>
          <me>
            Q =  N_{e}q_{e}
          </me>
              <me>
               or, \quad Q= (N_{atom})\times (Z) \times(q_{e}) 
              </me>
             where <m>N_{atom}</m> is number of atoms and <m>Z</m> is atomic number.
              <me>
            =  n \times N_{A} \times Z \times q_{e}
            </me>
            where <m>n</m> is number of moles and <m>N_{A}</m> is Avagadro's number.
             </p> 
             <p>
             = [(Mass of material, m)/(Molar Mass, M)](Avagadro's number, <m>N_{A}</m>) (Atomic Number, Z) (Charge on electron, <m>q_{e}</m>)
             </p>
             <p>
              <me>
              or, \quad Q  = \frac{m}{M}\times (N_{A})\times Z\times  q_{e} 
              </me>
              Here <m>Q</m> is total charge in material, <m>M</m> is mass number, in case of elemental material value of 
              mass number, A is same as molar mass, M.
             </p> 
             <p>
              <me>
                \therefore \quad Q_{+} = \frac{1000\,g}{244\,g/mol}\times (6.02\times 10^{23})(\#/mol)\times 94 \times (1.6\times 10^{-19}\,C)
              </me>
              <me>
                =3.7\times10^{7}\,C
              </me>
                </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
 
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          A hydrogen atom consists of a proton and an electron. If the radius of the atom is 
          equal to the Bohr radius of <m>0.5292 \times 10^{-10} \,m</m>, what is 
          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              the gravitational force between the two particles,
            </li>
            <li>
              the electrical force between the particles, and 
            </li>
            <li>
              the ratio of the electrical force to the gravitational force? 
            </li>
          </ol>
          <em>Note:</em> Newton's gravitational constant, <m>G  =  6.67\times 10^{-11} \,N m^{2}/kg^{2};</m>  
          Coulomb's Electrostatic constant, <m>k  =  9.00 \times 10^{9} \,N m^{2}/C^{2};</m> 
          mass of proton, <m>m_{p}  =  1.67 \times 10^{-27} \,kg;</m> 	
          mass of electron, <m>m_{e}  =  9.11\times 10^{-31} \,kg;</m> 
          charge of proton, <m>q_{p}  =  1.60 \times 10^{-19} \,C;</m> 
          and charge of electron, <m>q_{e}  =  -1.60 \times 10^{-19} \,C.</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
         Given: Radius of atom, <m>r  =  0.5292 \times 10^{-10} \,m.</m>
         <ol marker="a.">
          <li>
            From Newton's law of gravity, 
            <me>
              F_{g}  =  G\frac{m_{p}m_{e}}{r^{2}}  = 3.6\times10^{-47} \,N 
            </me>
            </li>
          <li>
            From Coulomb's law of electrostatics, 
            <me>
              F_{e}  =  k\frac{q_{p}q_{e}}{r^{2}} = 8.23\times10^{-8}\,N 
            </me>
              </li>
          <li>
            Ratio of two forces,
            <me>
              R = \frac{F_{e}}{F_{g}}= 2.27\times 10^{39} 
            </me>
             </li>
        </ol>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Three charges are located along the x-axis. The first charge of <m>+1 \,\mu C </m> is located at 
          <m>x = 0,</m> the second of <m> - 2 \,\mu C</m> is at x = 5 cm, and the third charge of <m>+3 \,\mu C </m> 
          is located in such way that there is no electrical force on it. 
          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              Where is the third charge located?
            </li>
            <li>
              What is the electrical force on the first charge?
            </li>
            <li>
              What is the electrical force on the second charge?
            </li>
          </ol>
            </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Given:	<m>q_{1}  =  1.00 \times 10^{-6} \,C;	\quad	q_{2}  =  -2.00 \times 10^{-6} \,C;</m>	
          <m>q_{3}  =  3.00 \times10^{-6} \,C; </m> <m>k  =  9.00 \times 10^{9} \,N m^{2}/C^{2};</m>
          <m>r_{12}  =  5 \times 10^{-2} \,m.</m>
          <image source="fig5a.png" width ="60%"> </image>
          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              Let the charges are located in a line as shown in figure below, 
              then magnitude of force on <m>3^{rd}</m> charge due to <m>1^{st}</m> and <m>2^{nd}</m> charges is given by 
              <me>
                |\vec{F}_{31}| = k\frac{q_{1}q_{3}}{r_{13}^{2}};
              </me>
              and 
              <me>
                |\vec{F}_{32}| = k\frac{q_{2}q_{3}}{r_{23}^{2}}
              </me>
              Since there is not net force acting on <m>3^{rd} </m> charge, [figure (a)] hence 
              <me>
                \vec{F}=\vec{F}_{31} + \vec{F}_{32} = 0
              </me>
              <me>
                \text{or,}\quad  k\frac{q_{1}q_{3}}{r_{13}^{2}} + k\frac{q_{2}q_{3}}{r_{23}^{2}} =0  
              </me>
              <me>
                \text{or,}\quad  \frac{q_{1}}{r_{13}^{2}} = - \frac{q_{2}}{r_{23}^{2}} 
              </me>
              <me>
                \text{or,}\quad \frac{ 1.00 \times 10^{-6}}{x^{2}} = \frac{ 2.00 \times 10^{-6} }{(r_{12}+ x)^{2}} 
              </me>
              <me>
                \text{or,}\quad  \frac{ 1}{x^{2}} = \frac{ 2}{(5 + x)^{2}} 
              </me>
              <me>
                \text{or,}\quad 2x^{2} = x^{2}+10x+25
              </me>
              <me>
                \text{or,}\quad x^{2} - 10x-25 =0
              </me>
              <me>
                \therefore\quad x = \frac{10 \pm \sqrt{100+4\cdot1\cdot25}}{2\cdot1}  = 12.1 \,cm, -2.1 \,cm
              </me>
               Here we have taken x = -2.1 cm  to obtain no net force on the <m>3^{rd}</m> charge.  
               Hence x=<m>r_{13}</m>=-2.1 cm = -0.02 m.
            </li>
            <li>
              <me>
                \vec{F}_{1}  =  \vec{F}_{12} +  \vec{F}_{13} 
              </me>
              <me>
                = k\frac{q_{1}q_{2}}{r^{2}_{12}} (\hat{i})+k\frac{q_{1}q_{3}}{r^{2}_{13}} (\hat{i})
              </me>
              <me>
                = 9\times 10^{-3}(800 + 7500)(\hat{i}) = 74.7 (\hat{i}) N 
              </me>
               here, <m>\hat{i}</m> is a unit vector along x-axis [figure (b)]. Here only magnitude of charges 
               are taken in calculation as the direction of forces are already determined according to nature of charges. 
            </li>
            <li>
              <me>
                \vec{F}_{2}  =  \vec{F}_{21}  +  \vec{F}_{23}  = 18.2 (-\hat{i}) N  
              </me>
              [figure (c)]
             </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Consider the three charges <m>1 \,\mu C,</m> <m>2 \,\mu C</m> and <m>-3 \,\mu C</m> located 
          at the three corners of a square. What is the magnitude and direction of the initial 
          acceleration of the <m>4 \,\mu C</m> charge at the fourth corner if mass of all the 
          charged objects are 2 kg each and are released from rest? Neglect gravity. 
          </p>
          <image source="fig5b.png" width="30%"> </image>
      </statement>
      <solution>
          <p>
          Given:	<m>q_{1}  =  1 \times 10^{-6} \,C;	\quad k  =  9.00\times 10^{9} \,N m^{2}/C^{2};</m>   
          <m> q_{2}  =  2 \times 10^{-6}\,C; \quad r_{2} =  0.1 \,m;</m> <m>q_{3}  =  -3 \times 10^{-6}\,C;</m>
          <m>r_{3} =  0.1 \,m;\quad q_{4}  =  4 \times 10^{-6}\,C;\quad m =  2 \,kg;</m>
        </p>
        <image source="fig5c.png" width="30%"> </image>
        <p>
          The direction of force <m>F_{41}</m> can be determined by 
          <me>
            \tan\theta  =  \frac{r_{24}}{r_{12}} \Rightarrow  \quad \theta= 45\,^{o}
          </me>
         <me>
          \text{Now,}\quad  r_{14}  =  \sqrt{r^{2}_{12}+r^{2}_{24}} = 0.1414\, m 
         </me>
         <me>
          \therefore\quad F_{41}  =  k\frac{q_{1}q_{4}}{r^{2}_{14}} =1.80 \,N;
         </me>
         <me>
          F_{42}  =  k\frac{q_{2}q_{4}}{r^{2}_{24}} =7.20 \,N;
         </me>
         <me>
          \text{and}\quad F_{43} = k\frac{q_{3}q_{4}}{r^{2}_{34}}= -10.80 \,N
         </me>
         Therefore force along x-axis on charge <m>q_{4}</m> is given by 
         <me>
          \sum F_{x} =  F_{41}\cos\theta -F_{43} = ma_{x} \Rightarrow \quad a_{x} = -4.76 \,m/s^{2}
         </me>
         and along y-axis is
         <me>
          \sum F_{y} =  F_{42} + F_{41}\sin\theta =ma_{y} \Rightarrow \quad a_{y} = 4.235 \,m/s^{2} 
         </me>
         <me>
          \text{Hence}\quad a  =  \sqrt{a^{2}_{x}+a^{2}_{y}} =6.45  \,m/s^{2}
         </me>
         <me>
          \text{and}\quad \tan\phi  =  \frac{a_{y}}{a_{x}} 
         </me>
         Therefore, <m>\phi =41^{o} </m> or, <m>139^{o} </m> from +ve x-axis.
          </p>
          <image source="fig5d.png" width="30%"> </image>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          A thin ring of charge <m>Q</m> and radius <m>a</m> is centered on the  x-axis in the y, z plane as shown in figure. 
          A point charge q is located a distance x from the center of the ring. 
          <image source="fig4.png" width="30%"> </image>
          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              What is the electrical force exerted by the ring on the point charge? 
            </li>
            <li>
              What is this force equal to when the point charge is at the center of the ring? 
            </li>
            <li>
              What is this force equal to when x is much greater than a?
            </li>
            <li>
              What is this force when <m>Q = 10 \,\mu C, \quad q = -5 \,\mu C, </m> a = 0.1 m, and x = 0.2 m? 
            </li>
          </ol>
           </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Given: <m>\epsilon_{o}=8.85\times 10^{-12}\,C^{2}/Nm^{2};</m> <m>Q=10\times 10^{-6}\,C;</m>  
          <m>q= -5\times 10^{-6}\,C;</m>   a = 0.1 m, x = 0.2 m.
        </p>
        <image source="fig6.png" width="30%"> </image>
        <p>
          Consider a differential charge <m> \,dQ</m> at the top of a ring of 
          length <m>\,ds</m>  so that it behaves like a point charge to obtain 
          a force acting on charge  q  at a distance  x  from the ring. 
          Hence, 
          <me>
            \frac{\,dQ}{Q}  = \frac{\,ds}{2\pi a}
          </me>
          as the charges are distributed uniformly on a ring. 
          <me>
            \therefore  \quad \,dQ = \frac{Q}{2\pi a}\,ds
          </me>
          where <m>2\pi a</m> = length of a ring.
            <me>
              \text{Now,}\quad \,dF=k\frac{\,dQ q}{r^{2}}, \quad  \text{where}\quad r=\sqrt{a^{2}+x^{2}}
            </me>
             <me>
              \therefore\quad \,dF_{x} =  dF\cos\theta = k\frac{\,dQ \,q}{r^{2}}\left(\frac{x}{r}\right) 
              = k\frac{\,dQ \,q}{r^{3}}x   = k\frac{\,dQ \,q x}{(a^{2}+x^{2})^{3/2}}
            </me>
              <me>
              \text{also,}\quad \,dF_{y} =  dF\sin\theta = k\frac{\,dQ \,q}{r^{2}}\left( \frac{a}{r}\right) 
              = k\frac{\,dQ \,q}{r^{3}}a = k\frac{\,dQ \,q a}{(a^{2}+x^{2})^{3/2}} 
            </me>
               <me>
              \therefore\quad F_{x}=\int \,dF_{x}   = k\frac{q x}{(a^{2}+x^{2})^{3/2}} \int \,dQ =k\frac{Q \,q \,x}{(a^{2}+x^{2})^{3/2}}
            </me>
            If we consider a differential charge <m>\,dQ </m> at the bottom, then y-component 
         of force cancels out each other at a charge q and hence similarly all the 
         y-components cancel out each other if we consider a differential charge at 
         any portion of the ring because of the charge symmetry, i.e., 
         <me>
          F_{y}=\int \,dF_{y}= 0
         </me>
         by charge symmetry.
        </p>
        <p>
          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <me>
                \vec{F}=F_{x}\hat{i}+F_{y}\hat{j}  = k\frac{Q \,q x}{(a^{2}+x^{2})^{3/2}}\hat{i}
              </me>
                 </li>
            <li>
              <m>\text{For} \quad x=0, \quad  F = 0</m>
            </li>
            <li>
              <m> \text{For}\quad x \gt \gt a,</m>
             we have <m>\quad 1 \gt \gt \frac{a}{x},</m>
             <me>
              \therefore\quad  \vec{F}= k\frac{Q \,q \,x}{x^{3}(\frac{a^{2}}{x^{2}}+1)^{3/2}} \hat{i}= k\frac{Q \,q}{x^{2}}\hat{i} 
             </me>
             which is Coulomb's law for point charges.
                </li>
            <li>
            <m>F=-8.05 \,N\hat{i}</m>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
</paragraphs>


<paragraphs>
  <title>Electric Field</title>
  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        An electric dipole has a negative charge of -10 nC  at point (-1.0 m, 0) and a positive 
        charge of  +10 nC  at point (+1.0 m, 0). What is its electric field at points 
        <ol marker="a.">
          <li>
            (0,0),
          </li>
          <li>
            (2 m,0)
          </li>
          <li>
            (0,1 m),
          </li>
          <li>(2 m,-1 m)</li>
          <li>What is the dipole moment of this dipole?</li>
        </ol>
         </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <image source="fig7.png" width="40%"> </image>
      <p>
        Given:	<m>q  =  10.0\times 10^{-9} \,C; \quad d  =  2.0 \,m; </m>	
        <m>k = 9.0\times10^{9} \,N.m^{2}/C^{2}</m>
        <ol marker="a.">
          <li>
            <me>
              \vec{E_{a}}=\vec{E_{1a}}+\vec{E_{2a}}
            </me>
            <me>
              \vec{E_{1a}} =k\frac{q}{r^{2}_{1a}}(-\hat{i}),\quad r_{1a} =1\,m; 
            </me>
            <me>
              \vec{E_{2a}} =k\frac{-q}{r^{2}_{2a}}(\hat{i}),\quad r_{2a} =1\,m 
            </me>
            <me>
              \therefore\quad \vec{E_{a}}=-180  (N/C) \hat{i}
            </me>
               </li>
          <li>
            <me>
              \vec{E_{b}}=\vec{E_{1b}}+\vec{E_{2b}}
            </me>
            <me>
              \vec{E_{1b}} =k\frac{q}{r^{2}_{1b}}\hat{i},\quad r_{1a} =1\,m;
            </me>
            <me>
              \vec{E_{2b}} =k\frac{-q}{r^{2}_{2b}}\hat{i},\quad r_{2b} =3\,m 
            </me>
            <me>
              \therefore\quad \vec{E_{b}}=8  (N/C) \hat{i} 
            </me>
               </li>
          <li>
            <me>
              \vec{E_{c}}=\vec{E_{1c}}+\vec{E_{2c}}
            </me>
            <me>
              \vec{E_{1c}} =k\frac{q}{r^{2}_{1c}}\left(\frac{-\hat{i}+\hat{j}}{\sqrt{2}}\right), \quad r_{1c} =\sqrt{2}\,m;
            </me>
            <me>
              \vec{E_{2c}} =k\frac{-q}{r^{2}_{2c}}\left(\frac{\hat{i}+\hat{j}}{\sqrt{2}}\right), \quad r_{2c} =\sqrt{2}\,m
            </me>
            <me>
              \therefore\quad \vec{E_{c}}=-63.6 (N/C)  \hat{i}
            </me>
               </li>
          <li>
            <me>
              \vec{E_{d}}=\vec{E_{1d}}+\vec{E_{2d}}
            </me>
            <me>
              \vec{E_{1c}} =k\frac{q}{r^{2}_{1d}}\left(\frac{\hat{i}-\hat{j}}{\sqrt{1^{2}+1^{2}}}\right), \quad r_{1d} = \sqrt{2}\,m;
            </me>
            <me>
              \vec{E_{2d}} =k\frac{-q}{r^{2}_{2d}}\left(\frac{3\hat{i}-\hat{j}}{\sqrt{3^{2}+1^{2}}}\right), \quad r_{2d} =\sqrt{10}\,m
            </me>
            <me>
              \therefore\quad \vec{E_{d}}=23.3 (N/C)  \hat{i} -29.0 (N/C) \hat{j} 
            </me>
            <me>
              = 37.2 (N/C) \left(\frac{23.3\hat{i}-29.0\hat{j}}{37.2}\right)
            </me>
               </li>
          <li>
            <me>
              \vec{p}=qd\hat{i}
            </me>
            <me>
              \therefore\quad  \vec{p}=2.0\times 10^{-8}(Cm) \hat{i}
            </me>
               </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        A water molecule has an oxygen ion of charge -2 e  at  the origin of a coordinate system and 
        two hydrogen ions of charge +1 e at a distance of <m>4.00\times 10^{-11} \,m</m>  
        making angles of <m>\pm 60^{o}</m> as shown in the figure below. The molecule is in an 
        external electric field of strength 100 N/C  directed above the x-axis at an angle of
         <m>45^{o}.</m> 
         <image source="fig8a.png" width="30%"> </image>
         <ol marker="a.">
          <li>
            What is the dipole moment of the molecule? 
          </li>
          <li>
            What is the electrical force on the oxygen molecule due to the external field. 
          </li>
          <li>
            What is the torque on the molecule? 
          </li>
          <li>
            What is the potential energy due to the dipole moment of the molecule? 
          </li>
             </ol>
              </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <image source="fig8b.png" width="30%"> </image>
      <p>
        Given: <m> q = 2 e; \quad  e = 1.60\times 10^{-19} \,C; \quad d = 4.00\times 10^{-11} \,m; </m>	
        <m>\theta = 60^{o};  \quad \phi = 45^{o}; \quad  E= 100 (N/C).</m>
        <ol marker="a.">
          <li>
            <me>
              \vec{p}=\vec{p_{1}}+\vec{p_{2}}
            </me>
            <me>
              \vec{p_{1}} =  e d(\cos\theta\hat{i}+\sin\theta \hat{j});
            </me>
            <me>
              \vec{p_{2}} =  e d(\cos\theta\hat{i}-\sin\theta \hat{j});
            </me>
            <me>
              \vec{p}=2e d\cos\theta \hat{i}=6.40\times 10^{-30}\,Cm \hat{i}
            </me>
             </li>
          <li>
            <me>
              F = q\vec{E} 
            </me>
            <me>
              \vec{E} =  E(\cos\phi\hat{i}+\sin\phi \hat{j});
            </me>
            <me>
              \vec{F} = 2.26\times 10^{-17}\,N(\hat{i}+ \hat{j}) 
            </me>
              </li>
          <li>
            <me>
              \tau=\vec{p}\times\vec{E} 
            </me>
            <me>
              \vec{p}=p\hat{i}; 
            </me>
            <me>
              \vec{E}=E\cos\phi\hat{i}+E\sin\phi \hat{j};
            </me>
            <me>
              \tau= \begin{bmatrix}
       \hat{i} &amp; \hat{j} &amp; \hat{k}\\
       p &amp; 0 &amp; 0 \\
       E \cos \phi &amp; E\sin \phi &amp; 0
       \end{bmatrix} = pE\sin\phi \hat{k}=4.53\times 10^{-28} \,Nm\hat{k}
            </me>
               </li>
          <li>
           <me>
            U = -\vec{p}\cdot\vec{E} = -pE = -4.53\times 10^{-28} \,J
           </me>
              </li>
             </ol>	
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>


  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        A thin rod of charge <m>Q</m> and length <m>2a</m> is centrally located along the y-axis. 
        <ol marker="a.">
          <li>
            Use calculus to show that the electric field at a point x along the x-axis is given by 
            <me>
              E  = k\left(\frac{Q}{x\sqrt{x^{2}+a^{2}}}\right)\hat{i}.
            </me>
              </li>
              <li>
                What does this become when <m>x \gt\gt a?</m>
              </li>
              <li>
                When <m>x \lt\lt a?</m>
              </li>
        </ol>
           </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <image source="fig12.png" width="35%"> </image>
      <p>
        Consider a charged rod of length 2a having linear charge density <m>\lambda.</m> 
        To find field at a point  P  from the center of the rod consider a small charge element 
        <m>\,dy</m> which behaves as a point charge <m>\,dq</m> then the field at  P  is given by 
         <me>
          \,dE=\frac{k\,dq}{r^{2}}
        </me>
       Due to charge symmetry the  y  components of field cancel out each other and only  x  
       components of field survived. Hence, 
       <me>
        \,dE_{x}=\,dE\cos\theta= \frac{k\,dq}{r^{2}}\frac{x}{r}  = \frac{kx\lambda\,dy}{r^{3}} 
        =\frac{kx\lambda\,dy}{\left(x^{2}+y^{2}\right)^{3/2}}
       </me>
          <me>
        \therefore\quad E=E_{x}=kx\lambda\int\limits_{-a}^{a}\frac{\,dy}{\left(x^{2}+y^{2}\right)^{3/2}}
       </me>
      Now solve this integrand first then substitute the limits. Let 
      <me>
        \mathscr{I} = \int\frac{\,dy}{\left(x^{2}+y^{2}\right)^{3/2}}
      </me>
      From geometry of the figure 
      <me>
        y=x\tan\theta
      </me>
           <me>
       \text{or,} \quad \,dy=x\sec^{2}\theta\,d\theta 
      </me>
             <me>
            \therefore\quad \mathscr{I} = \int\frac{x\sec^{2}\theta\,d\theta}{(x^{2}+x^{2}\tan^{2}\theta)^{3/2}} 
            = \int \frac{1}{x^{2}}\cos\theta\,d\theta   = \frac{1}{x^{2}}\sin\theta=\frac{1}{x^{2}}\frac{y}{r}
          </me>
          <me>
         = \frac{y}{x^{2}\sqrt{x^{2}+y^{2}}}
          </me>
                   <me>
            \therefore\quad  E= kx\lambda \left[\frac{y}{x^{2}\sqrt{x^{2}+y^{2}}}\right]_{-a}^{a} 
             = kx\lambda\frac{2a}{x^{2}\sqrt{x^{2}+a^{2}}}   = \frac{2k\lambda a}{x \sqrt{x^{2}+a^{2}}} 
          </me>
          <me>
          = \frac{kQ}{x \sqrt{x^{2}+a^{2}}}
          </me>
             As total charge on a rod is Q. If  <m>x\gt \gt a,</m>  then  
          <me>
            E= \frac{kQ}{x^{2}},
          </me>
           i.e., rod behaves as a point charge. 
         </p>
         <p>
          If <m> a \gt \gt x </m> then 
          <me>
            E=\frac{kQ}{ax}=\frac{2k\lambda}{x}
          </me>
          If rod is infinitely long then <m> E\propto\frac{1}{x}</m> as  k and <m>\lambda</m> are constant.
         </p>
         <p>
          <term>Alternative in vector form:</term>
          <me>
            \vec{dE}= k\frac{dq}{r^{2}}(\cos\theta\hat{i}-\sin\theta\hat{j});
          </me>
          Here, 
          <me>
            \left[\cos\theta=\frac{x}{r}\right] \quad \text{ and } \quad  \left[ \sin\theta=\frac{y}{r}\right]
          </me>
        <me>
           also, \quad \lambda=\frac{charge}{length}=\frac{\,dq}{\,dy}=\frac{Q}{2a}
          </me>
           <me>
           \text{or,} \quad \frac{\,dq}{Q}=\frac{\,dy}{2a}; 
          </me>
         <me>
          \therefore, \quad \vec{E}=\int\vec{dE}; \quad \text{and} \quad r=\sqrt{x^{2}+y^{2}}
         </me>   
              </p>
              <p>
                <ol marker="a.">
                  <li>
                    <me>
                      \vec{E}=\int k\frac{dq}{r^{2}}(\frac{x}{r}\hat{i}-\frac{y}{r}\hat{j})  
                      = \int k \frac{Q}{2a}\frac{dy}{r^{3}}(x\hat{i}-y\hat{j})
                    </me>
                                       <me>
                      = k\frac{Qx}{2a} \int\limits_{-a}^{a} \frac{dy}{(x^{2}+y^{2})^{3/2}}\hat{i}-k\frac{Q}{2a} \int\limits_{-a}^{a} \frac{ydy}{(x^{2}+y^{2})^{3/2}}\hat{j}
                    </me>
                    <me>
                      = k\frac{Qx}{2a} 2 \int\limits_{0}^{a} \frac{dy}{(x^{2}+y^{2})^{3/2}}\hat{i}-0 \cdot\hat{j} 
                    </me>
                    <me>
                      =  \left. k\frac{Qx}{a}\left(\frac{y}{x^{2}\sqrt{x^{2}+y^{2}}}\right)\right\vert_{0}^{a}\hat{i}   = k \left(\frac{Q}{x\sqrt{x^{2}+a^{2}}}\right)\hat{i} 
                    </me>
                      </li>
                      <li>
                        <me>
                          \vec{E}=k\frac{Q}{x^{2}}\hat{i} 
                        </me>
                        Field due to a point charge.
                                 </li>
                      <li>
                        <me>
                          \vec{E}=k\frac{Q}{ax}\hat{i} = \frac{1}{2\pi \epsilon_{o}}\frac{\lambda}{x}\hat{i}
                        </me>
                               </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Find the electric field at a point due to a uniformly charged Arc.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <image source="arc.png" width="35%"> </image>
      <p>
        Consider an arc of radius r and linear charge density <m> \lambda.</m>  
        To find the field at a point  O  consider a small charged element <m>\,dl </m> 
        which behaves as a point charge <m> \,dq</m> then field at  O is given by 
        <me>
          \,dE=\frac{k\,dq}{r^{2}}
        </me>
        Now due to charge symmetry components of field along y - axis cancels out each 
        other and only x-components are survived. Hence, 
        <me>
          \,dE_{x} = \,dE \cos\theta
        </me>
        <me>
          \therefore\quad E  = \int\,dE_{x} =\int\limits_{-\theta_{o}}^{\theta_{o}} \,dE \cos\theta 
           = \int\limits_{-\theta_{o}}^{\theta_{o}}\frac{k\,dq}{r^{2}}\cos\theta
        </me>
               <me>
          \text{or,}\quad E = \int\limits_{-\theta_{o}}^{\theta_{o}} \frac{k \lambda r \,d\theta}{r^{2}}\cos\theta 
        </me>
        <me>
          [\because \quad \,dq=\lambda\,dl\quad and \quad\,dl=r\,d\theta  ]
        </me>
        <me>
          \text{or,}\quad E  = \frac{k\lambda}{r}\int\limits_{-\theta_{o}}^{\theta_{o}}\cos\theta\,d\theta 
          =\frac{k\lambda}{r} \{\sin\theta\}_{-\theta_{o}}^{\theta_{o}}  = \frac{k\lambda}{r} \{2\sin\theta_{o}\} 
        </me>
         along x-axis.  If <m>\theta_{o}\rightarrow \pi </m> then arc becomes a circular ring and field at the center of ring is zero. 
           </p>
    </solution>
  </example>


  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Find the electric field at a point due to a uniformly charged ring.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <image source="ring.png" width="35%"> </image>
      <p>
        Consider a ring of radius  a  having total charge  Q.   To find the field at point  P  
        consider an elementary charge  <m>\,dq </m> then field at  P  is given by 
        <me>
          \,dE=\frac{k\,dq}{r^{2}}
        </me>
         Because of the charge symmetry,  y  components of field cancel out each other and 
         only  x  components survived. Hence,
<me>
  \,dE_{x} =\,dE\cos\theta=\frac{k\,dq}{r^{2}}\cos\theta = \frac{k\,dq}{r^{2}} \frac{x}{r}
</me>
<me>
  = \frac{k\,dq}{r^{3}} = \frac{k x \,dq}{(x^{2}+a^{2})^3/2}
</me>
<men xml:id="eqn-elf_ring1">
  \therefore \quad E= \int\,dE_{x} =\int \frac{k x \,dq}{(x^{2}+a^{2})^3/2} = \frac{k x Q}{(x^{2}+a^{2})^3/2} 
</men>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Find the  electric field at a point due to a uniformly charged disc.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <image source="disc.png" width="35%"> </image>
      <p>
        Consider a disc of radius <m>R</m> having total charge <m>Q</m> and uniform surface 
        charge density <m> \sigma. </m> To find the field at point <m>P</m> consider an 
        elementary charged ring of radius <m>r,</m> and thickness <m>\,dr </m> having charge 
        <m> \,dq </m> then the field at point <m>P</m> due to a ring is given by the eqn. <xref ref="eqn-elf_ring1"/>, i.e.,
        <me>
          \,dE = \,dE_{x}= \frac{k x \,dq}{(x^{2}+r^{2})^3/2}\quad \text{(along x-axis)}.
        </me>
        <me>
          \therefore\quad E = E_{x} =\int \,dE_{x} =\int\limits_{0}^{R}\frac{k x (\sigma 2\pi r\,dr)}{(x^{2}+r^{2})^3/2} 
        </me>
        <m>[\because \,dq = \sigma </m> (area of the ring)].
        <me>
          \text{or,}\quad E = 2\pi\sigma k x \int\limits_{0}^{R}\frac{r\,dr}{(x^{2}+r^{2})^3/2}
        </me>
        <me>
          \text{Now let}\quad \mathscr{I}= \int \frac{r\,dr}{(x^{2}+r^{2})^{3/2}} 
        </me>
        From geometry of the figure 
       <m> x^{2}+r^{2}=t^{2}</m>
        <me>
          \text{or,}\quad 2r\,dr=2t\,dt \quad \text{or,} \quad r\,dr=t\,dt
        </me>
        <me>
          \therefore\quad \mathscr{I}= \int \frac{t\,dt}{t^{3}} = \int t^{-2}\,dt = -\frac{1}{t} = \left(-\frac{1}{\sqrt{x^{2}+r^{2}}}\right)
        </me>
        <me>
          \therefore\quad E = 2\pi\sigma k x \left(-\frac{1}{\sqrt{x^{2}+r^{2}}}\right)_{0}^{R} 
          = -2\pi\sigma k x \left[ \frac{1}{\sqrt{x^{2}+R^{2}}}-\frac{1}{\sqrt{x^{2}+0}}\right]
        </me>
        <me>
         =2\pi\sigma k x \left[\frac{1}{x}-\frac{1}{\sqrt{x^{2}+R^{2}}}\right]
        </me>
        <me>
          \therefore\quad E=2\pi\sigma k \left[1-\frac{x}{\sqrt{x^{2}+R^{2}}}\right]
        </me>
        If <m> x=0</m> the field at the center of the disc (or, field near charged surface, <m>E=\frac{\sigma}{2\epsilon_{o}}</m>)
        <image source="gr1.png" width="35%"> </image>
        <me>
          or,\quad E =2\pi\sigma k = \frac{kQ}{R^{2}}\quad \text{(along x-axis).} 
        </me>
        <m>[\sigma=\frac{Q}{\pi R^{2}}]</m>
       
          If <m>x \lt \lt R,</m>
          <me>
            E=2\pi\sigma k [1-\frac{x}{R}]= 2\pi\sigma k
          </me>
          If <m>x \gt \gt R,</m> 
       <me>
        E=2\pi\sigma k [1-\frac{x}{x}]= 0 
       </me>
         </p>
         </solution>
  </example>


  <conclusion>
    <p>
      <term>Summary:</term> 
       <ol marker="i.">
          <li>
            Electric field due to point charge, 
            <men xml:id="eqn-disc1">
              E = \frac{kQ}{r^{2}}
            </men>
             along radial direction, i.e., <m>E\propto\frac{1}{r^{2}}.</m>
          </li>
          <li>
            Electric field due to charged rod, 
            <men xml:id="eqn-disc2">
              E = \frac{2k\lambda}{x}
            </men>
             along perpendicular to the rod  ie., <m>E\propto\frac{1}{x}.</m>
          </li>
          <li>
            Electric field due to charged plane, 
            <men xml:id="eqn-disc3">
              E = 2\pi\sigma k = \frac{2\pi\sigma}{4\pi\epsilon_{o}}= \frac{\sigma}{2\epsilon_{o}}  = constant  
            </men>
            and directed along perpendicular to the disc, ie., <m>E</m> is independent of the distance 
            between the disc and point of consideration as long as the point is near to the plane.
          </li>
        </ol>
       </p>   
  </conclusion>
 
   
  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Find the electric field at a point due to two oppositely charged infinite sheets.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <image source="fig13.png" width="35%"> </image>
      <p>
        The electric field outside a uniformly charged infinite sheet is 
        <me>
          E = \sigma/2\epsilon_{o}
        </me>
         where <m> \sigma </m> is the charge density <xref ref="eqn-disc3"/>. 
      </p>
      <p>
        <ol marker="a.">
          <li>
            Outside the two sheets, the electric field contributions due to the two sheets are equal 
            and opposite as shown in the figure. Therefore, they cancel one another producing 
            <m>E = 0.</m> 
          </li>
          <li>
            Between the two sheets, the electric field contributions due to the two sheets are equal 
            and parallel as shown in the figure. Therefore, they add to one another producing 
            <me>
              E=\sigma/\epsilon_{o}
            </me>
             directed away from the positive sheet and toward the negative sheet.
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        What is the electric field at the center of the hollow hemisphere bounded by <m>r=a,</m>
         <m>0 \lt \theta \lt \frac{\pi}{2}, </m>  and <m>0 \lt \phi \lt 2\pi</m> that carries 
         a constant surface charge density <m>\sigma</m> and radius <m>R</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <image source="hemiselec.png" width="35%"> </image>
      <p>
        Consider a strip on the hemisphere of radius <m>r=R\sin\theta </m> and 
        thickness <m>R\,d\theta.</m> The charge on the strip is given by
<me>
  \,dq=\sigma \,dA = \sigma 2\pi r \,dr = \sigma 2\pi R\sin\theta R\,d\theta 
</me>     
       Electric filed at the center <m>o</m> of the hemisphere  due to this strip is given by 
       <me>
        \,dE = \,dE_{z}=\,dE\cos\theta = \frac{\sigma k\,dq z}{(z^{2}+r^{2})^{3/2}}
       </me>
       <me>
        =\frac{\sigma k\,dq R\cos\theta}{(R^{2}\cos^{2}\theta+R^{2}\sin^{2}\theta)^{3/2}}
        = \frac{\sigma 2\pi k R^{3}\sin\theta\cos\theta\,d\theta}{R^{3}} 
       </me>
       <me>
     = \frac{\sigma}{2\epsilon_{o}}\sin\theta\cos\theta\,d\theta 
       </me>
       <me>
        \therefore E = \int \,dE = \frac{\sigma}{2\epsilon_{o}}\int\limits_{0}^{\frac{\pi}{2}}\frac{\sin 2\theta}{2}\,d\theta 
        =\frac{\sigma}{4\epsilon_{o}} \quad\text{along -ve z-axis}
       </me>
            </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        A charge  q = +200 nC  is located on a small object attached to a light string of length 1 m 
        attached to the top of a thin vertical rod of length 2 m as shown in figure below. 
        A charge  Q = +100 nC  is distributed uniformly throughout the rod. Due to electrostatic repulsion 
        the string makes an angle <m>\theta = 5^{o}.</m> What is the mass of the hanging object?
      </p>
      <image source="fig22.png" width="30%"> </image>
    </statement>
    <solution>
         <p>
          Given: <m> q = 2.00\times 10^{-7} \,C; \quad L = 1 \,m; </m> 
          <m>Q = 1.00\times 10^{-7} \,C; \quad \theta = 5^{o};</m> <m>\epsilon_{o} =  8.85 \times 10^{-12} \,C^{2}/N.m^{2}</m>
      </p>
      <p>
        <me>
          F_{x} = F-T\sin\theta =0
        </me>
        <me>
          F_{y} = T\cos\theta - W = 0
        </me>
        <me>
          \lambda=\frac{Q}{2L} =5.00\times10^{-8} \,C/m
        </me>
        <me>
          r=L\sin\theta =0.08716 \,m 
        </me>
        <me>
          E=\frac{2k\lambda}{r} =1.032\times 10^{4} \,N/C
        </me>
        <me>
          F=qE =2.063\times 10^{-3} \,N
        </me>
        <me>
          T=2.367\times10^{-2}\,N
        </me>
        <me>
          \therefore\quad m =2.406\times10^{-3}\,kg
        </me>
           </p>
    </solution>
  </example>
